4 …
5 (2) Any person who is the survivor of a law enforcement officer, correctional
6 officer, probation officer, firefighter, volunteer firefighter, or rescue squad
7 worker killed as a direct result of a traumatic injury sustained in the line of
8 duty.
9 (3) The spouse of a law enforcement officer, correctional officer, probation
10 officer, firefighter, volunteer firefighter, or rescue squad worker who is
11 permanently and totally disabled as a direct result of a traumatic injury
12 sustained in the line of duty.
13 (4) Any child, if the child is at least 17 years old but not yet 24 years old, whose
14 parent, legal guardian, or legal custodian is a law enforcement officer,
15 correctional officer, probation officer, firefighter, volunteer firefighter, or
16 rescue squad worker who is permanently and totally disabled as a direct result
17 of a traumatic injury sustained in the line of duty. However, a child's eligibility
18 for a waiver of tuition under this Chapter shall not exceed: (i) 54 months, if
19 the child is seeking a baccalaureate degree, or (ii) if the child is not seeking a
20 baccalaureate degree, the number of months required to complete the
21 educational program to which the child is applying.
22 …."
